generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]},{"name":"Or","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally the name of the god of thunder in Norse mythology, Thor (Old Norse <i>Þórr</i>). It was not used as a personal name during the Middle Ages. The modern name is either a late 18th-century revival of the god's name or else a vernacular development of   Tord ."],"variants":[{"name":"Thor","meanings":["Originally the name of the god of thunder in Norse mythology, Thor (Old Norse <i>Þórr</i>). It was not used as a personal name during the Middle Ages. The modern name is either a late 18th-century revival of the god's name or else a vernacular development of   Tord ."]}]},{"name":"Aliax","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Alex  , used only as a feminine name. Its formation has probably been influenced by   Alice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Matilda Or Aliax Erdington was born about 1282, in Surrey, England, United Kingdom, her father, William Henry de Erdington Lord of Shawbury, was 35 and her mother, Maud Somery, was 47. She had at least 3 sons with Sir Knight John de la Lee I, Lord of Roden."},"et":{"Abt 1282–":"umbes 1282–Surnud","1272–Male":"1272–Surnud","1274–1343":"1274–1343","1282–Female":"1282–Surnud","1298–Male":"1298–Surnud","1338–1372":"1338–1372","1344–Male":"1344–Surnud","1352–1415":"1352–1415","1248–1282":"1248–1282","1237–1302":"1237–1302","1352":"1352","1274":"1274","1372":"1372","1272":"1272","1282":"1282","1338":"1338","1415":"1415","1237":"1237","1248":"1248","Abt 1282":"umbes 1282","1302":"1302","1344":"1344","1343":"1343","1298":"1298","Of Wolksted Estate, , Surrey, England":"Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kings Hill, Staffordshire, England":"Kings Hill, Staffordshire, England","Woking, Surrey, England,  “Odo’s Estate” William The Conquerer’s 1/2 Brother":"Woking, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1282–":"noin 1282–Kuollut","1272–Male":"1272–Kuollut","1274–1343":"1274–1343","1282–Female":"1282–Kuollut","1298–Male":"1298–Kuollut","1338–1372":"1338–1372","1344–Male":"1344–Kuollut","1352–1415":"1352–1415","1248–1282":"1248–1282","1237–1302":"1237–1302","1352":"1352","1274":"1274","1372":"1372","1272":"1272","1282":"1282","1338":"1338","1415":"1415","1237":"1237","1248":"1248","Abt 1282":"noin 1282","1302":"1302","1344":"1344","1343":"1343","1298":"1298","Of Wolksted Estate, , Surrey, England":"Surrey, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kings Hill, Staffordshire, England":"Kings Hill, Staffordshire, England","Woking, Surrey, England,  “Odo’s Estate” William The Conquerer’s 1/2 Brother":"Woking, Surrey, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Englant